# rocprof-compute overlay for ROCm @VERSION@

## TL;DR

The in-distribution `rocprof-compute` command on `$PATH` for `rocm-@VERSION@`
fails at startup because it's a Python wrapper whose dependencies were
never installed (`astunparse`, `colorlover`, etc.).  This overlay
provides a working `rocprof-compute` without touching the original ROCm
distribution: a nuitka onefile binary under `lib/`, a `bin/`
symlink, and a `prepend_path("PATH", ...)` line in the corresponding
Lmod modulefile.

## Layout

```text
rocprof-compute/
├── README.md          (this file)
├── install.sh         idempotent wire-up: ensures lib/ + bin/ symlinks
│                      and edits the modulefile to prepend our bin/ to PATH
├── build.sh           idempotent nuitka rebuild from upstream tag rocm-@VERSION@,
│                      drops a fresh binary into lib/
├── bin/
│   └── rocprof-compute    -> ../lib/rocprof-compute.bin
├── lib/
│   └── rocprof-compute.bin   either (a) symlink to the working but un-wired
│                             /shared/apps/ubuntu/opt/rocm-@VERSION@/bin/rocprof-compute.exe
│                             (shipped by the ROCm package),
│                             OR (b) a fresh nuitka onefile produced by build.sh
└── build/                   work directory populated by build.sh
```

## Rationale

The fix is *purely* a wiring repair: the working binary is already on
disk in every affected ROCm prefix as `rocprof-compute.exe`, but the
`rocprof-compute` symlink that the user actually invokes was wired to
the Python wrapper at `${ROCM_PATH}/libexec/rocprofiler-compute/rocprof-compute`
which aborts on missing pip dependencies.  The overlay shadows that
broken symlink via PATH ordering — the original distribution bytes are
untouched and the change reverts cleanly by unloading the rocm/@VERSION@
module.

@DETAIL_BLOCK@

## Reproducing the fix on a fresh cluster install

```bash
cd /shared/apps/ubuntu/opt/rocm-patches-@VERSION@/rocprof-compute
./install.sh                  # shim mode (uses the in-distribution .exe)
# OR
sbatch --time=01:00:00 ./build.sh  # build a fresh nuitka onefile, then:
./install.sh
```

Both end with the same wiring; the difference is whether
`lib/rocprof-compute.bin` is a symlink to the in-distribution binary
or a freshly-compiled file with documented provenance.

## Verification

```bash
module purge && module load rocm/@VERSION@
which rocprof-compute
# expected: /shared/apps/ubuntu/opt/rocm-patches-@VERSION@/rocprof-compute/bin/rocprof-compute
rocprof-compute --version
rocprof-compute analyze --help | head -10
```

